{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20782"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20782"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.1,0.35,0.35,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97351"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13657"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79957"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12630"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97351"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old child presents with fever, sore throat and a widespread rash. Examination reveals a punctate erythematous rash on the trunk and limbs, circumoral pallor, and a red swollen tongue with prominent papillae. The skin shows early hyperkeratosis and scaling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following microorganisms is most likely responsible for this clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corynebacterium diphtheriae","Listeria monocytogenes","Streptococcus pyogenes","Staphylococcus aureus","Enterococcus faecalis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E (Group A Streptococcus) is the causative organism of scarlet fever. The clinical presentation described is classic for scarlet fever, which is characterized by pharyngitis, fever, and a distinctive rash. The rash is caused by an erythrogenic toxin produced by certain strains of \u003Cem\u003ES. pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E. The characteristic features include a punctate erythematous rash, circumoral pallor, and a strawberry tongue (red, swollen tongue with prominent papillae).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause skin infections and toxic shock syndrome but is not the typical cause of scarlet fever. While some strains of \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E can produce exfoliative toxins that cause skin manifestations, the classic scarlet fever presentation with circumoral pallor and strawberry tongue is associated with \u003Cem\u003ES. pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterococcus faecalis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes urinary tract infections, endocarditis, and intra-abdominal infections but is not associated with scarlet fever or the described rash pattern.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorynebacterium diphtheriae\u003C/strong\u003E causes diphtheria, which presents with a characteristic pseudomembrane in the throat rather than the described rash pattern. Diphtheria may cause a toxic appearance but does not produce the classic scarlet fever rash.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes meningitis, septicaemia, or gastroenteritis, particularly in immunocompromised individuals, pregnant women, and neonates. It does not cause the clinical presentation described for scarlet fever.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScarlet fever is most common in children between 3 and 15 years of age. The rash typically begins to fade after 3-4 days, followed by desquamation (peeling) of the skin, particularly on the fingertips, toes, and groin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Scarlet fever is caused by group A Streptococcus (Streptococcus pyogenes) producing erythrogenic toxin.","Classic features of scarlet fever include punctate erythematous rash, circumoral pallor, and strawberry tongue.","Scarlet fever typically affects children between 3 and 15 years of age and is associated with pharyngitis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 361."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79957"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20782"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79957"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T06:55:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T12:37:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13657"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97351"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44